Instructs an LLM to generate the `.ctx` context document for a single leaf source file, replacing whatever exists there. This is the prompt template consumed by the summarization pipeline's per-file (non-directory) worker.

The prompt defines the contract for leaf-level `.ctx` files specifically: prose-only, no fixed schema, framed as what a teammate needs to edit the file without opening it. It enumerates exactly five content categories to cover (non-obvious behavior, coupling/wire-format dependencies, notable function signatures, invariants, non-obvious crate dependencies), and a matching set of banned filler phrases and anti-patterns (no diffs/history, no "this file contains," no restating the same fact twice). The embedded example (session-token module) is the calibration anchor for length, register, and density — any edit to the rules should keep that example consistent with the prose rules stated above it, since the example is doing double duty as both illustration and de facto spec.

This file has a sibling, likely `prompts/summarizer-branch.md` (or similarly named), which defines the analogous contract for directory-level `.ctx` files that summarize child summaries rather than source code — the two prompts share vocabulary ("context document," "consumed by another LLM under a context budget") and should be kept stylistically consistent if one is edited. Nothing in this file depends on runtime code; it's pure prompt text with no executable logic, so "editing" it means revising instructions/rules/example, not fixing behavior.